{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Sino-Cape Verdean|Cape Verde|China|filetype=svg}}

'''Cape Verde–People's Republic of China relations''' refers to the [[bilateralism|current and historical relationship]] between the [[People's Republic of China]] and [[Cape Verde]]. The two states established [[bilateral relations]] in April 1976, shortly after Cape Verde gained independence from the [[Portuguese Empire]]. Cape Verde is an adherent to PR China's [[One China Policy]]. China maintained relations with Cape Verde throughout from 1970s to mid-1990s mainly to prevent the [[Taiwan|Republic of China]] (Taiwan) from gaining Cape Verde's international recognition through [[checkbook diplomacy]]. However, in the mid-1990s, a number of Chinese capitalists began investing in the island nation and relations grew during the 2000s as a result.<ref>[http://csis.org/blog/china-cape-verde-dragon%E2%80%99s-african-paradise China in Cape Verde: the Dragon’s African Paradise] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100209172038/http://csis.org/blog/china-cape-verde-dragon%E2%80%99s-african-paradise |date=February 9, 2010 }} CSIS by Loro Horta</ref>

==Economic development==
Since the first [[Forum on China Africa Cooperation]] conference in 2000, the Chinese government has successfully delivered $63.5 million in development finance.<ref>Austin Strange, Bradley C. Parks, Michael J. Tierney, Andreas Fuchs, Axel Dreher, and Vijaya Ramachandran. 2013. China’s Development Finance to Africa: A Media-Based Approach to Data Collection. CGD Working Paper 323. Washington DC: Center for Global Development. http://aiddatachina.org/projects?utf8=%E2%9C%93&search=&active_string%5B%5D=Active&country_name%5B%5D=Cape+Verde&scope_names%5B%5D=Official+Finance{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> These projects include $4.4 million for construction of the Poilão dam in the Santa Cruz, $22 million to build a sports stadium in Monte Vaca, and $2.3 million in debt forgiveness.<ref>Austin Strange, Bradley C. Parks, Michael J. Tierney, Andreas Fuchs, Axel Dreher, and Vijaya Ramachandran. 2013. China’s Development Finance to Africa: A Media-Based Approach to Data Collection. CGD Working Paper 323. Washington DC: Center for Global Development. http://aiddatachina.org/projects?utf8=%E2%9C%93&search=&active_string%5B%5D=Active&country_name%5B%5D=Cape+Verde&scope_names%5B%5D=Official+Finance{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
During the 2010 Forum for Economic and Trade Cooperation between China and Portuguese speaking countries in Macau, Wen Jiaobao announced the creation of a $1 billion fund aimed at boosting trade between China and Portuguese speaking countries.<ref>Austin Strange, Bradley C. Parks, Michael J. Tierney, Andreas Fuchs, Axel Dreher, and Vijaya Ramachandran. 2013. China’s Development Finance to Africa: A Media-Based Approach to Data Collection. CGD Working Paper 323. Washington DC: Center for Global Development. http://aiddatachina.org/projects/797{{dead link|date=November 2016 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>

